Pragois public transport (MHD) will introduce the chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will get on the metro, trams and buses, which instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, it is accessible for about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day coupon (it will be valid from 1 January 2009) and both have it registered on their smart card in the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency) information points and offices, located in the Muzeum, Můstek, NádraĆ Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letääany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy coupons by internet on the Dopravní podnik web pages: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who will start using the online store can finally forget the ticket counters in the metro stations, where they had until now to trample with impatience in long queues in order to obtain paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon via internet and will be recorded on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these contact points, passengers are provided with a counter with trained staff, who will help them with the purchase by internet and, in addition, will record the coupon they bought on their card," says the spokesperson for the Martin Opatrný project.
Next to the libraries, it will also be possible to record the electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, remind the machines to compost the tickets and the passengers have perhaps already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," said Opatrný.
An automaton will control the coupon instead of the driver
The automatons that will work from tomorrow are easy to use.
Simply insert the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
E-coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also around the city.
