The Sudetes called for a referendum in the USA
The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This follows from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some Sudeten German groups allegedly addressed the US President with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov in the letter ask the US President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of the Šumava is dearly attached".
Since the rallying of Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, attitude without regard, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state outside of us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter million of the inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, he would simply have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some waited for the United States and Great Britain to achieve a certain type of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," says Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, according to him, believed that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way of characterising the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport is planning to launch on Wednesday.
The Office of Minister Aleš Öeb+ek believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, the internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast and drinking while driving.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to reach the consciousness of young drivers, bikers and pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also reflected in the "bloody" slogan of the whole campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think" is capitalized on the license plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay."
Which must symbolize that one can pay for life for a moment of inattention.
The spots will "hanter" the spectators until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in Anglo-Saxon countries, where one can see commonly images with drastic images of the victims of accidents.
He believes that this will lead to a decrease in the rate of accidents and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The strategy of sugar and whipping against drivers
"What works with drivers is the system of sugar and whip.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time, when they burn a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded to the drivers," says Martin Kön, the transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative advertisements, the psychologist believes.
According to him, signs that signal the danger to drivers are already less effective.
"When a static panel that warns against a danger is installed, it will probably soon merge with the environment and the drivers won't notice it again," Koñn said.
