Nights of insomnia for Hypo Real Estate shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted only a few weeks ago.
What a chance that the politician would use the word 'relatively' and that he would slip that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This one happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a credit of one billion to protect itself from the turbulences of the markets.
One person in confidence told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are granted up to EUR 35 billion.
The Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, the company-daughter Depfa bears the losses.
According to a newspaper article, the state financier had refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible because of distrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 per cent to €2.37 million, and the equity rate had also slightly decreased from 1.6 per cent to 1.45 per cent.
Profits in progress and those net of financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period in the previous year, profits from the allocation of specified claims and securities and the termination of provisions in credit transactions had fallen from more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it was only because of the large profits derived from the repayment of the downstream accounting costs resulting from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the repayment of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern companies that the earnings deficit of about 16 percent proved to be moderate.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had initially speculated badly on industrial loans for real estate, which had subsequently been filialized to Aareal Bank.
Because traditional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa then became more involved in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private investors and the State (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and internationally diversified.
On the value of the daughter company, Hypo Real Estate must carry out depreciations which should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group's gains and losses, which is still rather vague.
The fact of the matter is that the dividends have been cut off.
Already for 2007, they had been truncated to two thirds.
Since the takeover of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing in the inter-bank market since it has no customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of credit between banks again fell considerably, as banks accumulated their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate requires an annual portion - about 50 Billion euros - of all Depfa's loans for a short-term refinancing average.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing requirement is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets that are currently largely out of business.
Other sources say that refinancing would be ensured through the funds until the end of 2009.
The Chairman of the Executive Board of HRE Georg Funke, on the other hand, explained that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to resort to medium-term financial markets.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for the Supervision of Financial Services (Bafin) assume that the market capacity of the Hypo Real group is now assured.
The bank's shareholders and creditors can only hope for this.
However, given the dynamics and imponderability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But neither can the opposite be ruled out.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest press releases, still at the gates of insolvency on Sunday at the end of the evening, this rescue, at least temporary, will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are particularly good.
While debt in the first place has barely moved, the price of second-rate loans is falling.
The most affected are the investment funds of the former daughter company Württemberg Hypo and of course those that have a life beyond 2009.
The bonds of the bank Hypo Real Estate previously seemed to be an alternative speculation investment, now their value must be regarded as dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the very institute which brought the crisis into the establishment by the takeover of the bank Depfa.
As long as issuers, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, it can be assumed that there will be a reduction in arrears over time.
Or will happen what no one dares hope at the moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome within the next 15 months.
But in the face of renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability that approached safety has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should reserve nights of insomnia primarily for long-term creditors on whether to separate themselves from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn a line to carry forward losses for the next few years to the next tax on capital income from automatically collected stock gains.
