Rats also have sensations
A rat or cockroach flees from danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having until now been able to prove it just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the questions of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter hard-to-use terrains because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists derive a comparable subjective experience.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At the very least for these aspects of our consciousness which depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from the other primates.
Another significant peculiarity might lie in the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being related to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if the consciousness were not to depend on the language, it would surely influence it, so that the animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ a lot from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, both internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analysed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses major problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness next to it that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
