"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no black clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where we discover with intimate gestures and stolen eyes artists who do not care to get on stage.
German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of a few stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the program of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "on the street" are artists able to transmit passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience on stage.
To capture moments of personality of these artists it is not necessary to make photos on stage.
They have their own personality and character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera moments of personality of flamenco stars ".
Bauer began a long trip to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera in 1997 with the festival "Chant populaire des Mines".
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the equipment, rememorize classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dancing or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for the essentials and the magic was the constant of this work that we present these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has been transformed into a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in a book collecting portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits de vieux sportifs" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a more or less long time.
I think that in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don't know or who just leave you for a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco which is entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited in the Gallery El Fotómata, located at number 20 of the rue de la Mata (rue parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) which will be open until October 16.
