The interview - Blood becomes safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating yesterday the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Dr.Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the grunt of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, which sought to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for a disaster to be prevented.
While Justice Krever was late in tabling his report, some provinces then established a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," says Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
With efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field in the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Decary keeps in mind, however, that "trust is something extremely fragile."
From its inception, on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease were hatching in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells the story of the one that has held the fort since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations in the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when this is not known and a serious disease can result, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration and inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
As a result, in April 1999, the blood of those who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was denied.
A few years ago, however, it was shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle we applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique was introduced on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The NATs have shortened the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors may become infected without knowing it and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health," says the Chief Executive Officer of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year on Reunion Island the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," says Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
"Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
Because anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
A healthy person, 18 years of age and older, who meets the eligibility criteria, can give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of blood proposers are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Since today's life is so frantic, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye globes and skin that is almost exclusively used for burn victims.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to collect more than one thousand a year.
We should start proposing transplants early next year," says Decary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Several moms are disappointed to be unable to access it", because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
