Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Canadian Mining Executive Vice-President, Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has brought a defamation suit of six million against three authors and a small publishing house with no money in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable money to prepare their defence and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of mining.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frighten anyone who dares to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas rather than batons.
It was therefore enough for mining to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he could both ask for a "public" debate while disregarding the views of the same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag chase (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just put out a formal warning against Black Canada authors intimidating them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal discourse, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on academic research freedom and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is not possible to study and discuss issues that displease the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada authors.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has a long history of managing debates and disagreements and resolving conflicts.
The disproportionate pursuit of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republican and Democratic, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months is yet to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
It provides, inter alia, for better control by elected representatives of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, and a right of scrutiny of the salaries paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
The U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruptions to the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would cause on the mood of investors.
The deadline agreed was for the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the U.S. presidential election, who were late associated with the negotiations, were rather in favour of the agreement, but they were still dissatisfied that they were forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the agreement to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the agreement on the salary of the leaders of the state-backed companies.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be welcomed.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
Asked on another channel to find out if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I have read [show] that this is something that we are all going to have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsaleable debts of U.S. financial institutions.
After 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then spread to other, more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs), leading to a liquidity freeze and the debanda of banks and financial institutions.
It's a group of elected Republicans who blew up the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed that this impasse has been overcome since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round out the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision has also been added stating that if the government were to bear losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which may be added another 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be endorsed by another Congress vote.
In exchange for its assistance, Washington will obtain shares in the rescued companies that will earn it dividends in the event of a profit and that it will be able to resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing on housing loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and severance benefits paid to the managers of the affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Votes continued yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Obviously, Washington cannot hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that takes advantage of taxpayers."
Animator of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economics teachers, including three Nobel laureates, have written to tell us: Congress is asked not to rush and to consider carefully the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was refusing to acquire its competitor in full sinking since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risk housing loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and 10 largest insurers.
"This is not money lost," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, we get back a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that the times are uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalizing another bank that had been misled by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all loans outstanding at Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) in real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and accounts receivable of the British bank.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
