What could Zuschlag &amp; Company make in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damage. Other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and the use of forgery.
According to the prosecution, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the state and the municipalities, about HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other, in the pockets of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing bills of fees, behind which no actual services were provided and thus, the associations never fulfilled their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books from the Józsefváros market, while they manufactured the stamps at Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's statement, he had to find pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they would introduce, among others, from the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as from the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlags in 2003, this place restored a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which later became known as Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors of form and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and up to ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
The overly imaginative bill issuers also fell into excess, when they mentioned Pigal Kft, a company also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor that of Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor's office.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, told the website hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew, immediately, that they were fake documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the invoice, a hundred people have lodged there, also did not stick, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much room.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The issuers of zealous invoices also did not ask themselves about Budapest travel agencies, being part of their choice, but only organizing trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also runs counter to the accounting practices of the agency.
They added VAT on these documents, while services relating to travel activities, the destination of which is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices issued on behalf of the Hotel Revfülöp to Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services do not bear a 25% VAT as stated, but a 15% VAT. Moreover, the hotel employees issue only printed invoices, while the fakes were written by hand.
The public prosecutor's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes by referring to the carriage of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, since its profile was the investment consultancy.
Moreover, it was also for defects of form, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont proved to be false.
Just as in the case of the Ravenna Bt. company or the Kunfehértó sports course, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Nor did the forgers pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the company's liquidator denies having issued this invoice.
Deliberately established invoices
Another category of invoice issuers is that of those who were fully aware that they were required to issue fictitious invoices.
The Foundation Esely Budapestért Alapítvány, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták grouping, issued an invoice to the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért, for a sum of HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was led to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, Atlasz Egyesület Association and Vörösfenyő Egyesület Association, for an amount of approximately HUF 5 million, but behind which no services were actually provided.
No financial movement took place, either, as the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this was avoided by the organizations in their accounts.
The following category of companies issuing invoices is that of companies directly related to the accused.
For example, the administrative representative of the general manager of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest but where he could not be found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, worth approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of the company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov was also reported to have sent documents relating to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he pocketed their value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies functioned, as the accused explains by the fact that they did not receive work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused as well as editor of the founding documents of the companies, he drew up invoices in their names, to the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
Kubatov gave a total of 15 invoices to organizations issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution believed that 10% of the sums indicated on the invoices as well as VAT went in Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used Szi-Beri Bt. to produce fictitious invoices which were used in the context of Biztos Pont's grant application.
In January 2006, the Association Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA) for a grant.
They obtained this grant for an amount of HUF 500,000 twice, but these amounts were not used for the objectives indicated in the application.
To prevent this from happening, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were submitted to the TMA.
Moreover, these invoices were found during the search of the office of Árpád Kemecsei at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the accused will relate the method of making the invoices, as she had already done before the prosecution.
What could be really interesting would be that the main accused, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confession is not very detailed, and although he has promised on several occasions to tell every detail, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest or, possibly, the Socialists would have reached an agreement that, in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the HUF 50 million, Zusi would carry the hat alone.
Today, he is probably offended, as requests for house arrest, based on a reduction in his conditions of detention, continually fall into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and those who commit non-repairable economic crimes, walk freely or at least, wait in their own homes for the end of the proceedings. He does not have that possibility.
The psychology of over auction: why is more money being spent?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have been able to update the neurological and economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a fun auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which was the overauction of a third party, the whole under the brainstem, called striatum, was moving intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
At the time, three groups were outbid by a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus made their bid.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an extra $15, as a reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost this money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is that the emphasis in one group was on victory, while in the other, on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were prepared to higher bets than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation." - noted Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When do we need to consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that one hundred thousand people are infected with the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand are being treated. This is due to the fact that often the patients do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases produced differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, are spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended that they be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated food, usually accompanied by poor overall condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stool becomes lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, one million people die of the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients is receiving medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know they are infected with the virus, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a sneaky way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: those who had a blood transfusion prior to 1991, drug users and tattooed.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult with your treating physician as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does he who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers at Oxford University carried out an interesting experiment by analysing at what level belief in God could influence tolerance to human pain.
As part of this bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing the electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look continuously at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the ermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while Da Vinci's choice of painting, not very different from the former, concerned its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while watching either the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
The Catholics declared that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "in safety", as someone who is "cared for" and they "quieted, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious themes, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that one can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that one finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image against which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
The results of this research were welcomed by Anglican bishop Tom Wright.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, actually changes our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, it remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if one shows the believers a Madonna painted by Leonard or by a painter of the same calibre?
Would seeing a better Virgin Mary bring better results?
