On the occasion of its tenth anniversary, Google says that it can be found in the bottom of people's pockets in the same way as the sky above their head. It knows where they spent their holidays, which specialists they consult and what are their interests.
Yet it is not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the influential people of society.
While as far as skeptics are concerned, establishing a parallel with Orwell's horror vision, they do not see the essentials of web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary for Google’s founders to meet their original goal, which sounded like: “Let’s get all the world’s information into a system!”.
According to the Google leader interviewed, after ten years of global upheaval work, they are still only at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all the information.
To the question: what will there be in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What is the job that would be best for me?". However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, when they will know enough about the users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used during Internet searches, the IP address of the computer that starts the search and the pages that are then viewed by the interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they have searched for, what they have clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long term, Recommendations, a program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us based on our previous statements and our registered preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if he looks at what my job is? ask users, who worry about seeing Google's monopoly of information.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can cause fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can cause Internet users to counter-reaction.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the terms sought are not only registered, but in justified cases, they are passed on to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most resounding example of recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian paedophiles, during which Google transmitted to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing an identification.
Human rights-conscious Internet users were able to sigh a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arm-on with the electronic legal protection agency EFF, proved its right in court against the FBI. According to the ruling rendered, in the future Google will still not be able to be compelled by any of the constitutional points to disclose information about the FBI's secret request, of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms it had won in relation to the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But in the end, it did not succeed in obtaining the lists of searches of private users, nor the entire list of websites and keywords of the past two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is castigated by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their private sphere and private domain suffer from it when they start using Google services. Therefore, they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is manifested against multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "savageons" bringing together enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic computer users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big companies, the "connected body", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, categorised as an invader of the world because of Windows, even though both fight for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The document code and the package of programs, continually refreshed, has a much more accessible effect, younger and cooler, faced with the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very exactly the problematic relationship between human rights and the internet, and what web 2.0, the most proclaimed key word of recent years, is right behind it.
Indeed, web 2.0 does not concern anything other than collaboration, that the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the channels of communication made available to us, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can hold a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other services, such as Twinter, or to last.fm, which is linked to his musical habits. Then, he can link them to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also hold blogs, in which appear automatically their most recent photo galleries that they store on Flickr or Picasa.
While we can see many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands in view of the morning photos, taken by the circle of common friends, with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that dismissed one of her employees, just for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about top management, we can be sure of one thing: the term of privacy is totally to be reconsidered nowadays.
The one who lives an online life, is made up of what he shows by himself, and this is how one can define the principle hiding behind the behaviour of young people today.
He wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to bypass Google's monopoly, can do so (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them is not the least. Google’s online services, including word processing, image processing and reading information, can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not linked to huge server parks and which do not assemble our best profile, which has existed to date.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its present value of 156 billion dollars, is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars). AdWords/AdSense advertising domains threaten the turnover of advertising agencies, while the services introduced at an increasing speed cause serious migraines not only to Microsoft, but to many other creators of computer programs.
However, the critical observers find, beside all this, contradictions with worrying effects: for example, the company's top management refused, in its entirety, the employee protests, after it doubled the price of the kindergarten and after the company deemed too expensive the daily multiple restoration, taken at any time. All this seems ridiculous beside the fact that already in 2006, Google acquiesced before the Chinese government and according to the terms of their agreement, the company detects all the results that hurt the good taste, as well as the interests of the Chinese regime.
According to one of the company's internal rules, the new services are not announced only when they can be used. What is sure is that in the coming months and years, they will move the world on new points. While some think that Google's project to scan and archive books and magazines is taking on such important dimensions that the company will soon find itself facing the U.S. Supreme Court, others are shaking at its Health system, because in it one can build a complete medical profit from our previous analysis results, our doctors and our problems.
The fact that Google builds a genetic database can give a good raw material to the next generation of science fiction authors. The novel by the famous Cory Doctorow, written with Orwellian half-tones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in a frightening way through Google data alone.
