The smart car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, other than the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, the bees'.
In the amazing project presented at the CATEEC in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea to start with, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-roboted system, type BR23C, which it equipped with bee qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval in shape, which in reality, looks very much like our secure protective hull - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the department research and development and public relations technology of the brand.
The bee's faceted eye plays a key role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the faceted eye, engineers approached the idea of the laser rangemeter.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into an avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
"If it wasn't for that, the mini-auto robot couldn't react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotised car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where collision is considered inevitable for the time being.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can be only two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we were only able to use rotary motion, acceleration and slow down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a larger energy concentration, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should deal with only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous manoeuvres. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant avoidance technology. Nissan estimates that this system will make its entry into mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
