The written version of the $700 billion economic rescue plan, which aims to buy back the banks' dubious credits, and to be used in multiple instances, is ready.
In the first round, half of this money will be spent.
Reuters announced that during further debates extending until after midnight, Saturday, local time on the east coast, Congress leaders had agreed on the controversies that had existed for days and days, around the rescue plan totalling $700 billion.
"We have taken a serious step forward" - said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the American House of Representatives, according to which all that remains is to put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born from the plan, is supported by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
The U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, commented on the outcome of the compromise that the program will work and will be effective, but other measures still need to be implemented. According to Pelosi, there is no question here of the rescue of Wall Street, but of turning the machinery of the economy in the other direction.
The written version of the plan was made public prior to the opening of Asian markets on Sunday evening at 8 p.m., local time in Washington (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., according to the local time in Central Europe), but did not cause a dramatic rise in the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill responding to the name of the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008. Then, its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then, the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are pleased with the progress achieved tonight, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, spokesperson for the White House.
Moreover, the program diverges from the Bush administration's original proposal, which stated that the $700 billion had to be spent at one time, for the redemption of securities for doubtful credits.
From now on, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be issued immediately after Congress passes the law, probably on Monday. This first amount will be used by the Treasury Secretary to buy bad debts from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the President's discretion.
The program will be overseen by an independent agency, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The spending of the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new congressional decree.
Under the Act, the Treasury Secretariat may develop a combined strategy: it may, at the same time, purchase bad debts, securities relating to bad mortgages and bad mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" debts.
The department's competent officials have stated that buybacks can take place not only at an auction but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance programme, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools at the origin of the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated that the law provides the necessary tools to spend $700 billion for the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the vast buyback of bad debts, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of seeing the system leading to the collapse of one or the other major financial institution.
"We will make the necessary arrangements, to be ready for the application of the law, as soon as it is signed" - he added.
On the other hand, bank managers who are in bad positions and waiting for state assistance can expect their severance pay, simply referred to as gold parachutes across the Atlantic, to be capped by the government.
Wage caps are only mentioned in specific cases, and limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat provides assistance to the firm.
The cap principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back through an auction, they will levy a surplus of tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the redemption of bad debts, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the leaders is not exaggerated.
In order for the picture to be complete, it must nevertheless be added that the existing golden parachutes are not changed. The cap applies only to new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
This is the first time in the history of the United States that legal caps will be in force regarding the appointments of directors general - commented the chairman of the committee in charge of the financial benefits of the Chamber of Deputies, the Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the state acquires a right to acquire shares in the banks taking part in the plan. In this way, the risk of taxpayers decreases, since they can even win in the case as soon as the economy and with it the banks saved fall back on their feet.
The bill mentions that in the next five years, the President must introduce a proposal to Congress that will rule on how the losses will be returned to taxpayers, from the financial sector.
On both sides, there were obviously those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That's not why American citizens mandated us, it doesn't protect taxpayers' dollars - said California Republican MP Darrell Issa.
His fellow Democrat from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believes that it is the same people who are pressuring action, as those responsible for the Wall Street collapse.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic selling prices in the processing industry were only slightly higher by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first of all, bag and belt manufacturing with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, followed by shoe production with a monthly increase of 2.5 per cent.
Higher prices for plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and chemical manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
Deflation resulted in oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and apparatus manufacturing (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in wood processing (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry saw an increase, ranging from 0.2 percent to 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a significant share of domestic industrial production, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly as a result of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of processing sectors, oil processing prices experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices rose by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices rose by 11 per cent.
Price decreases occurred in the textile and textile products production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
For the processing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the internal trade groups and according to sector allocation, in August, it was the sectors that initiated profit-on-investment that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-generating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent was recorded.
Export selling prices for the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar, compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
