Járóka said: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, hosted by France, began as a representative of the current presidency of the European Union.
In his message to the plenary, Lívia Járóka, MEP Fidesz European People's Party, as one of the main spokesmen of the expert consultation, drew attention to segregation in education, as it is a violation of the law that most affects Roma children and therefore one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among those invited to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of legal protection and European civil bodies, in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the group of deputy Fidesz People's Party, Járóka warned that in addition to the distinctions made during hiring, Roma disappear from the labour market, in the first place, as a result of their low qualifications.
"An overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have secondary school diplomas, and as a result of poor quality elementary education, only a very small proportion have the possibility of obtaining a higher education diploma."
Moreover, Járóka stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in the promotion of other fundamental rights.
Investment in the early education of Roma children means a strengthening of the economies of the member countries of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these reports in the widest possible circle, also between Roma and non-Roma.
The sooner a Roma child starts school, the more likely he or she is to become a productive member of the labour market; through taxes paid from income and consumption, he or she contributes to the State budget.
"By virtue of their citizenship of the European Union, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education, and be protected from low quality and sectarian education." - stressed Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, a European Union collaboration aimed at an objective and action is necessary for an immediate acceleration of the process of desegregation of schools. To this end, compliance with the existing anti-discrimination directives and in preparation is of paramount importance.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and the unemployed must be broken, and the opportunities provided by democracy must be given to Roma children so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe" - demanded Járóka.
On behalf of the "European Year for Equal Opportunities" for all, the objective of the Summit for Equal Opportunities in Europe, which has been organised every year since the Berlin Summit last year, is to provide a single platform to support measures aimed at promoting equal opportunities and combating discrimination, both at European level and at Member State level.
