Mp3 reader pointed at the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 players, can cause permanent injury to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a press release in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"from this scientific report we read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable musical devices, for more than 1 hour per day per week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume, can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data- pursues the manager Ue- this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What is most important is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can follow the new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"Scientists-concluded the Ue- Executive confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable and similar musical devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these data well using solutions such as reducing noise levels and exposure times.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum level of noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for extended periods of time risk permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
