The elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion bailout plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its moderate East Coast soul, favoring federal institutions as well as business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the Washingtons" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the central and southern states.
The soul, precisely, that made itself felt despotically with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been quoted is just one example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake is announcing or is already letting go: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and can be not just here.
In both the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have been inundated for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the revitalisation, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of sovereign state, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with abroad, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in a single country, in a single State.
This immediately creates a political problem for whom it governs: that is to say, to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation really seems out of the question, or it does not have much to say: the obvious proof is provided to us by the European Union, which, as usual, is divided between the various interests and between the various national strategies, cannot decide on any common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that all expect interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all an affection of credits: when we are going through a difficult period, there are only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in place.
They also have the means and the legitimization to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever dispose of in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is in perfect harmony with the ever-important importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
. Paradoxically, indeed, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at one stroke, that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather unmaterial things like water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but that are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more maps than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species that have turned out to be inadequate and full of shade.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: discredit, suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus further increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of majorities.
In short, The demand for leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and branched movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the "improvised electoral revolts" or, in the collective changes of these last few days, from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, the fall of the Labourers in Great Britain, the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not happen by chance).
We have the impression that traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, have ever more difficulty, which is not of today, to understand and thus to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is strengthening, increasing and potentially agitating in a disproportionate way.
In view of all this, talking about a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda, seems frankly exaggerated.
But it is said that keeping your eyes wide open is not without reason.
The superglue to walk on the walls.
Overcome the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centres, and today a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to hold a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
STUDY- The American journal Science published the findings of researchers from Dayton University, Akron, Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular carbon structure, called nano carbon tubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged as a stack of spaghetti." explains Zhong Lin Wang of Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glasspaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time that it "is easily detached from the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at Dayton University's Faculty of Engineering.
Walking on the wall? – “this material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers are thinking of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since nano carbon tubes are conductive of heat and electric current.
Other applications may include aerospace engineering.
For now, no superhero.
OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated to finding a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive made up of microfibers like hair, which self-cleans dust during movement on an area to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
Medicines: Never with fruit juices.
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed mainly in the summer because they are detoxifying and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital medicines, alter the absorption amplifying or decreasing, depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he launched a new alarm: a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice is enough to reduce the absorption of certain vital drugs, cancelling their beneficial effects and putting patients at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been strongly criticized for being responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic drugs, antibiotics, anxiolytics, anti-statinals and neurological drugs, up to toxic levels.
MEDICINAL PRODUCTS AT RISK- It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which gave the news in a two-year-old newsletter, warning doctors and patients not to under-estimate the danger deriving from this mix and to pay attention to what one drinks, if one takes medicines such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT THAT PAMPLEMOUSSE- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active substances inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
From there, Michele Carruba, Director of the Department of Pharmacology of the Public University of Milan, called: "These discoveries are usually immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies that will have to change the information notes of the medicines if necessary.
It is always necessary to read the illustrative papers of the medicines that are taken, and if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist," stressed the expert to the Ansa agency.
