When the energy comes out of the waves, now the big ones are throwing themselves.
This is an disproportionate deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface area and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colossus like Chevron have laid eyes, and now try to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has now been studied for a hundred years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was set aside, but now environmental authorities and the new increase in oil are giving a big boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity requirement could be covered by sea swell operating systems.
This amount would be twice that of nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colossae to attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy was the Energis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
With two years to go, more and more candidates among these companies, which have always been dedicated to traditional energy, rely on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying technologies on ocean energy," said the spokesperson for a company associated with the US oil colossus, the economic daily Wall Street Journal, "and is assessing the possibilities of cooperating with us."
